    "discriminators": [
     "UCS: 'distant rumbles to sharp thunder cracks.' Both ends of that range are the same thing physically: a broadband low-frequency burst with a long decaying rumble tail. Overwhelming sub-200 Hz energy and a very dark centroid make this one of the few signal_separable WEATHER entries.",
     "Versus EXPLOSIONS-REAL: acoustically close -- both are LF bursts with tails -- but thunder's tail is much longer and more diffuse (atmospheric propagation, kilometres of path) and it has almost no high-frequency crack compared with a real detonation.",
     "UCS: 'combination RAIN & THUNDER may best go into WEATHER-STORM' -- if the file has a continuous rain bed under it, its stationarity rises and STORM should win."
